-275-5}}\n* Meditation & The References From Various Religions \u2013 [https://www.shivashaktiyoga.org/shivashaktiyogablog/what-is-meditation/ What is Meditation].\n* {{cite book |author=Baba, Meher |author-link=Meher Baba |title=''Discourses''|url=http://www.discoursesbymeherbaba.org|publisher=Sheriar Foundation |location=Myrtle Beach, SC |year=1995 |pages=|isbn=978-1-880619-09-4 |oclc=|doi=}}\n* Cooper, David. A. ''The Art of Meditation: A Complete Guide''. {{ISBN|81-7992-164-6}}\n* [[Eknath Easwaran|Easwaran, Eknath]]. ''[[Passage Meditation|Meditation]]'' (see [[Passage Meditation|article]]). {{ISBN|0-915132-66-4}} new edition: ''[[Passage Meditation]]''. {{ISBN|978-1-58638-026-7}}. ''The Mantram Handbook'' {{ISBN|978-1-58638-028-1}}\n* Glickman, Marshall (2002) ''Beyond the Breath: Extraordinary Mindfulness Through Whole-Body Vipassana. {{ISBN|1-58290-043-4}}\n* [[S. N. Goenka|Goenka, S. N.]]. ''Meditation Now: Inner Peace through Inner Wisdom'', {{ISBN|1-928706-23-1|978-1-928706-23-6}}\n* {{Cite book | last1=Hanson | first1=Rick | last2=Mendius | first2=Richard | year=2009 | title=Buddha's Brain: The Practical Neuroscience of Happiness, Love, and Wisdom | publisher=New Harbinger Publications | isbn=978-1-57224-695-9 | url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781572246959 }}\n* Hart, William. ''Art of Living, Vipassana Meditation'', {{ISBN|0-06-063724-2}}, {{ISBN|978-0-06-063724-8}}\n* [[Jiddu Krishnamurti|Krishnamurti, Jiddu]]. ''This Light in Oneself: True Meditation'', 1999, [[Shambhala Publications]]. {{ISBN|1-57062-442-9}}\n* Heller, Rick. ''Secular Meditation: 32 Practices for Cultivating Inner Peace, Compassion, and Joy \u2013 A Guide from the Humanist Community at Harvard'', 2015, New World Library. {{ISBN|978-1-60868-369-7}}\n* Levin, Michal. ''Meditation, Path to the Deepest Self'', [[Dorling Kindersley]], 2002. {{ISBN|978-0-7894-8333-1}}\n* [[Barry Long|Long, Barry]]. ''Meditation: A Foundation Course&nbsp;\u2013 A Book of Ten Lessons''. {{ISBN|1-899324-00-3}}\n* Meditation for Beginners without Religion \u2013 [http://jhana8.com/meditation-for-beginners-secrets-for-success/ Meditation for Beginners].\n* Meiche, Michele. ''Meditation for Everyday Living''. {{ISBN|0-9710374-6-9}}\n<!-- note \"Paramahamsa Sri Nithyananda\" and other permutations have been previously deleted, and deleted again, watchout for nithyananda's spammers-->\n* Monaghan, Patricia and Eleanor G. Viereck. ''Meditation: The Complete Guide''. {{ISBN|1-57731-088-8}}\n* Oldstone-Moore, Jennifer. ''[https://books.google.com/books/about/Understanding_Confucianism.html?id=hwnbAAAACAAJ&redir_esc=y Understanding Confucianism]'', Duncan Baird, 2003. {{ISBN|1-904292-12-7}}.\n* {{Cite book | last1=Saraydarian | first1=Torkom | year=1976 | title=The Science of Meditation | publisher=TSG Publishing Foundation | isbn=978-0-911794-29-8 }}\n* [[Mahamandaleshwar Swami Shankarananda (Shiva Yoga)|Shankarananda, Swami]]. ''Happy For No Good Reason'', Shaktipat Press, 2004. {{ISBN|978-0-9750995-1-3}}\n* [[Vethathiri Maharishi]]. ''Yoga for Modern life''.\n* [[Ernest Wood|Wood, Ernest]]. [http://static.livingcosmos.org/ebooks/ernest-wood/ldump2/ ''Concentration&nbsp;\u2013 An Approach to Meditation.''] [[Theosophical Publishing House]] 1949. {{ISBN|0-8356-0176-5}}.\n* [[Paramahansa Yogananda|Yogananda, Paramahansa]]. ''[[Autobiography of a Yogi]]''.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Infobox medical intervention (new) |image=|caption=|ICD10=|ICD9=|MeshID=D019122|OPS301=|other_codes=|HCPCSlevel2=}}\n{{Sister project links|Meditation}}\n* {{curlie|Society/Religion_and_Spirituality/Meditation/|Meditation}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/topic/meditation-mental-exercise Meditation] at [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]\n\n{{Religion topics}}\n{{Meditation}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Meditation| ]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Articles with inconsistent citation formats]]\n[[Category:Concepts in the philosophy of mind]]\n[[Category:Concepts in the philosophy of science]]\n[[Category:History of psychology]]\n[[Category:Mind]]\n[[Category:Mind\u2013body interventions]]\n[[Category:Personal development]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of mind]]\n[[Category:Religion articles needing expert attention]]\n[[Category:Spiritual practice]]\n[[Category:Spirituality]]\n[[Category:Silence]]\n[[Category:Yoga]]\n", "name_user": "Terimo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDictionary definitions:I reconstructed some of the sentences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meditation"}
{"title_page": "David Banner", "text_new": "{{About|the musician|the television character in ''The Incredible Hulk'' television series|The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = David Banner \n|background = solo_singer\n|image = David Banner at FOB Brassfield-Mora 2009-01-26 3.jpg\n|caption = Crump in January 2009, performing for American soldiers at FOB Brassfield-Mora, Iraq\n|birth_name = Lavell William Crump\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1974|4|11}}\n|birth_place = [[Brookhaven, Mississippi]], U.S.\n|origin = [[Jackson, Mississippi]], U.S.\n|education = [[Southern University]], [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], U.S. \n|genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]] <!-- Please read http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#Genre \"The genre or genres of music performed by the act. Aim for generality (e.g. [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]] rather than [[East Coast hip hop]]).\" -->\n|occupation = {{flatlist|\n* [[David Banner discography|Rapper]]\n* songwriter\n* [[David Banner production discography|record producer]]\n* [[#Personal life|activist]]\n* philanthropist\n* actor\n}}\n|instrument = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sampler (musical instrument)|Sampler]]\n* [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]]\n}}\n|years_active = 1994\u2013present\n|label= {{flatlist|\n* A Banner Vision\n* [[E1 Music|E1]]\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n* [[SRC Records|SRC]]\n* Big Face}}\n|associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Crooked Lettaz]]\n* [[9th Wonder]]\n* [[Akon]]\n* [[ASAP Rocky]]\n* [[Big K.R.I.T.]]\n* [[Fiend (rapper)|Fiend]]\n* [[Kevin Rudolf]]\n* [[Lil' Flip]]\n* [[Lil Wayne]]\n* [[Pimp C]]}}\n|website = {{URL|http://davidbanner.com}}\n}}\n'''Lavell William Crump ''' (born April 11, 1974), known professionally as '''David Banner''', is an American rapper, record producer, actor, activist, and philanthropist.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://davidbanner.com/db/biography/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-09-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919132259/https://davidbanner.com/db/biography/ |archive-date=2018-09-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Brookhaven, Mississippi]], Banner's family moved to [[Jackson, Mississippi]] where he was raised. Banner graduated from [[Southern University]] and pursued a masters of education at the [[University of Maryland Eastern Shore]]. He started his music career as a member of the rap duo, [[Crooked Lettaz]], before going solo in 2000 with the release titled ''[[Them Firewater Boyz, Vol. 1]]''.\n\nIn 2003, Banner signed to [[Universal Records]] releasing four albums: ''[[Mississippi: The Album]]'' (2003), ''[[MTA2: Baptized in Dirty Water]]'' (2003), ''[[Certified (David Banner album)|Certified]]'' (2005), and ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told (David Banner album)|The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'' (2008).\n\nBanner is also a noted [[record producer|producer]], having produced music for himself, [[Trick Daddy]], [[T.I.]], [[Lil Boosie]] and [[Lil Wayne]] among others.\n\n==Early life==\nLavell William Crump was born in Brookhaven and raised in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], the elder son of Zeno Crump, Jr (May 22, 1951 \u2013 June 17, 2007), Jackson district fire cap master,<ref>https://www.dailyleader.com/2007/06/21/zeno-crump-jr</ref><ref name=\"XXL\"/> and Carolyn Crump. He graduated from [[Provine High School]] in Jackson in 1992 and then attended [[Southern University]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], his mother's alma mater.<ref name=\"Provine grad\">{{cite web|url=http://orig.clarionledger.com/news/0306/16/o01.html|title=Provine grad scores big!|author=Watkins, Billy|work=The Clarion-Ledger|date=June 16, 2003|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120715205018/http://orig.clarionledger.com/news/0306/16/o01.html|archivedate=July 15, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"tough questions\">{{cite web|title=Tough Questions for David Banner|url=http://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2003/may/19/tough-questions-for-david-banner/|work=Jackson Free Press|accessdate=November 9, 2016|date=May 19, 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031001181816/http://www.jacksonfreepress.com/cover_comments.php?id=1040_0_9_0_C|archivedate=October 1, 2003|url-status=live}}</ref> At Southern University, Crump served as president of the Student Government Association and received a [[bachelor's degree]] in business.<ref>{{cite web|last=Houston|first=Danielle|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2006/08/david_banner_hes_a_business_man/|title=David Banner: He's a Business...Man!|work=Vibe|date=August 10, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422225426/http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2006/08/david_banner_hes_a_business_man/|archivedate=April 22, 2008}}</ref> He later attended the [[University of Maryland Eastern Shore]] to pursue a [[master's degree]] in education but later left the program to pursue his music career full-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/davidbanner/articles/story/5935328/banner_brings_it|title=Banner Brings It |last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|date=2003-07-15|work=Rolling Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013173824/http://rollingstone.com/artists/davidbanner/articles/story/5935328/banner_brings_it|archivedate=October 13, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1480936/20031204/banner_david.jhtml|title=David Banner To Send Five Lucky Fans To College|last=Patel|first=Joseph|date=2003-12-04|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hhnlive.com/features/more/486|title=David Banner: Man On Fire|last=Davis|first=Dione|date=2008-09-23|work=HHNLive.com|accessdate=2009-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090628142255/http://hhnlive.com/features/more/486|archivedate=2009-06-28}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n\n===1994\u20132000: Beginnings and ''Them Firewater Boyz, Vol. 1''===\nCrump's stage name \"David Banner\" is taken from the lead character of the television series, ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]''.<ref name=\"VH1 interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1474718/20030724/banner_david.jhtml|title=David Banner: Mississippi Burning|last=Bottomley|first=C|date=July 24, 2003|publisher=VH1|accessdate=December 28, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001130531/http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1474718/20030724/banner_david.jhtml|archivedate=October 1, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> With several of his friends, Banner sent some demo tapes to Jackson, Mississippi radio station, [[WJMI]]. In 1999, Banner and rapper Kamikaze as the duo, Crooked Lettaz, released ''Grey Skies'' ([[Penalty Recordings]]).<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p366511/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Crooked Lettaz: Biography|last=DaRonco|first=Mike|publisher=allmusic|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> In 2000, Banner released his solo debut album, ''Them Firewater Boyz, Vol. 1''. Released on the independent label, Big Face Records, the album sold around 7,000 copies.<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=12526|title=David Banner: Can't Tell Me Nothin'|date=July 30, 2007|work=XXL|accessdate=December 28, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410174944/http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=12526|archivedate=April 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2003&ndash;06: ''Mississippi: The Album,'' ''MTA2: Baptized in Dirty Water'' and ''Certified''===\nAfter assessing various offers, Banner and manager, Scott Johnson, decided to sign with [[Universal Records]] subsidiary, [[SRC Records]], which was founded by [[Steve Rifkind]] who had previous success as CEO of the heavyweight hip-hop label, [[Loud Records]].<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_ScottJohnson_int.html |title=Interview with Scott Johnson|publisher=[[HitQuarters]]|date=10 Mar 2004 |accessdate=21 Dec 2010}}</ref> In 2003, Banner produced [[T.I.]]'s single, \"[[Rubberband Man]]\", which reached #30 on the Hot 100, #15 on the R&B chart, and #11 on the Rap chart. In 2003, Banner released his first major label album, ''[[Mississippi: The Album]]''. ''Mississippi'' included the hit single, \"[[Like a Pimp]]\", featuring [[Lil Flip]]. \"Like a Pimp\" peaked at #48 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, #15 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart, and #10 on the [[Hot Rap Tracks]] chart.<ref name=\"singles\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p441465/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}}|title=David Banner: Charts & Awards: Billboard Singles|publisher=allmusic|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}</ref> He released the follow-up album the same year titled ''[[MTA2: Baptized in Dirty Water]]'' which yielded the hit, \"Crank It Up\", featuring [[Static Major]].\n\nIn 2005, Banner released his third major label album, ''[[Certified (David Banner album)|Certified]]''. The album's first single was \"Ain't Got Nothing\" which featured Magic & [[Lil Boosie]], followed by the second single, \"[[Play (David Banner song)|Play]]\", which reached #7 on the Hot 100 chart, #5 on the R&B chart, and #3 on the Rap chart.<ref name=\"singles\"/> The third single, \"Touching\", featured Jazze Pha and reached #54 on the R&B chart. In 2006, Banner appeared on \"Seein' Thangs\", a song about Hurricane Katrina featured on DJ Shadow's album \"The Outsider\". A remix featuring Bay Area hyphy rappers Nump and Gold also was made. Outside projects for Banner have included writing the theme song to the video game, ''[[Saints Row (video game)|Saints Row]]'', as well as contributing to the music for a commercial promoting the video game, ''[[Marvel vs Capcom 3: Fate of Two Worlds]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/727/727105p1.html|title=Saints Row Snags David Banner|work=IGN|accessdate=9 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126072208/http://music.ign.com/articles/727/727105p1.html|archivedate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Banner played the part of Tehronne in ''[[Black Snake Moan (film)|Black Snake Moan]]''.\n\n===2007&ndash;present: ''The Greatest Story Ever Told'' and ''The God Box''===\nBanner appeared on the [[Adult Swim]] cartoon show [[That Crook'd 'Sipp]], which premiered Sunday, May 13, 2007. His single \"[[Play (David Banner song)|Play]]\" was used as the background music in the pilot's first television promo. In 2007, he played the character of Mo, in the film ''[[This Christmas (film)|This Christmas]]''. Banner also starred as Jay, a gang leader from the hood in ''[[Stomp the Yard: Homecoming]]''. On July 15, 2008, Banner released his fourth major label album, ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told (David Banner album)|The Greatest Story Ever Told]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theblackspotlight.com/news/David_Banner_Releases_The_Greatest_Story_Ever_Told.html|title=The Black Spotlight|accessdate=9 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004104633/http://www.theblackspotlight.com/news/David_Banner_Releases_The_Greatest_Story_Ever_Told.html|archivedate=4 October 2011}}</ref> The album's first single titled \"9mm\" featured [[Akon]], [[Lil Wayne]], and [[Snoop Dogg]]. Banner then produced his next two singles: \"[[Get Like Me (David Banner song)|Get Like Me]]\" featuring [[Chris Brown (American singer)|Chris Brown]] and [[Yung Joc]], \"Get Like Me\" reached #16 on the Hot 100, #7 on the R&B chart, and #2 on the Rap chart.<ref name=\"singles\"/> and \"[[Shawty Say]]\", featuring Lil Wayne. In 2008, Banner was featured on the track, ''Superfriend'', from the 2008 album, ''[[The Sound (Mary Mary album)|The Sound]]'', by [[gospel music|gospel]] [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] duo, [[Mary Mary]].\n\nIn 2010, he played Bosch in the film [[The Experiment (2010 film)|The Experiment]]. He has also worked with international artists such as Seeda, a Japanese Rap Artist where he was featured in the song,  Life Song in 2010 on Seeda's Breathe Album. Banner released his debut mixtape titled ''[[Sex, Drugs and Video Games]]'' on May 22, 2012 as a free download.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/David-Banner-Sex-Drugs-Video-Games-mixtape.349642.html|title=David Banner - Sex, Drugs & Video Games|work=DatPiff|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> It is also available on his website, davidbanner.com, where fans are encouraged to make a donation of at least $1 for the sixteen song mixtape.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T9QMrfBKUB8|title=David Banner's Epic Interview|date=9 April 2012|work=YouTube|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> The first single off the mixtape is titled \"Amazing\" featuring [[Chris Brown (American singer)|Chris Brown]]. It was announced that [[Universal Republic Records]] was going defunct, all of the artists on the roster moved from the label including (David Banner) was being moved to [[Republic Records]] making the label itself revived.\n\nIn 2013, David Banner appeared in the music video for the song ''[[Confessions (Lecrae song)|Confessions]]'' by [[Lecrae]]. Banner played Earl Gaines, Cecil Gaines' father, in the 2013 film ''[[The Butler]]''. Banner plays Jay, a criminal who is interrogated, in the 2014 film ''[[Ride Along (film)|Ride Along]].'' David Banner was featured on a remix of Mexican American rapper [[Kap G]]'s single \"La Policia\", which stirred hype throughout the media and the internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/04/09/kap-g-ti-david-banner-la-policia-remix|title=T.I. and David Banner Join Kap G For Powerful \"La Policia\" Remix|work=The FADER}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Activism===\nIn November 2006, Banner was awarded a Visionary Award by the National Black Caucus of the State Legislature to go to the park and crash some parties in recognition of his work after Hurricane Katrina going swisshhhh swishhhhhhh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wapt.com/video/10424269/index.html?%20taf=jac/|title=David Banner Speech|date=29 March 2012|work=WAPT|accessdate=9 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926235155/http://www.wapt.com/video/10424269/index.html?%20taf=jac%2F|archivedate=26 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn September 25, 2007, Banner testified before Congress at a hearing about throwing candy at mean people and hitting them with turkey meat. [[racism]] and [[misogyny in hip hop culture|misogyny in hip hop music]] titled ''From [[Don Imus#Rutgers women's basketball controversy|Imus]] to Industry: The Business of Stereotypes and Degrading Images''.<ref name=\"washington\">Abrams, Jim. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/25/AR2007092500908.html \"House Panel Debates Hip-Hop Lyrics\"]. ''[[The Washington Post]]'', September 25, 2011.</ref> He defended his use of offensive language and argued: \"Change the situation in my neighborhood and maybe I'll get better.\"<ref name=\"washington\"/> In his opening statement, Banner stated: \"I can admit there are some problems in hip hop but it is only a reflection of what's taking place in our society. Hip hop is sick because America is sick.\"<ref name=\"Hearing\">{{cite news|last=Leeds|first=Jeff|title=Hearing Focuses on Language and Violence in Rap Music |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/26/washington/26rap.html|work=The New York Times|date=2007-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|David Banner discography|David Banner production discography}}\n\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Them Firewater Boyz, Vol. 1]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Mississippi: The Album]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[MTA2: Baptized in Dirty Water]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Certified (David Banner album)|Certified]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told (David Banner album)|The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The God Box (album)|#TheGodBox]]'' (2017)\n\n;Collaborative albums\n* ''[[Death of a Pop Star]]'' {{Small|(with [[9th Wonder]])}} (2010)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\