{"title_page": "African Group", "text_new": "{{Infobox United Nations\n| image         = Emblem of the United Nations.svg\n| name         = Group of African States\n| map        = \n| map_size   = \n| map_caption      = \n| type         = [[United Nations Regional Groups|Regional group]]\n| abbreviation     = GAFS\n| leader_title  = Head\n| leader_name         = \n| status       = Active\n| formation  = {{start date and age|1964|df=yes}}\n| headquarters = \n| website      = \n| parent_organization       = \n| subsidiaries = \n| footnotes    = {{Portal-inline|Politics|size=tiny}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Group of African States''', or '''African Group''', is one of the five [[United Nations Regional Groups|United Nations regional groups]] and is composed of 54 Member States from the [[Africa]]n continent. The African Group is the largest regional group, and compose 28% of all United Nations members\n\nThe Group, as with all the regional groups, is a non-binding dialogue group where subjects concerning regional and international matters are discussed. Additionally, the Group works to help allocates seats on United Nations bodies by nominating candidates from the region.<ref name =\"UNU Report\">{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors=Agam, Hasmy, and Sam Daws, Terence O'Brien and Ramesh Takur |date=26 March 1999 |title=What is Equitable Geographic Representation in the Twenty-First Century |url=http://archive.unu.edu/unupress/equitable.pdf |publisher=United Nations University |page= |docket= |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Volger |editor-first=Helmut |encyclopedia=A Concise Encyclopedia of the United Nations |url=http://www.mu.edu.et/iphc/images/Tourism/ebooksclub.org__A_Concise_Encyclopedia_of_the_United_Nations__2nd_Edition.pdf |access-date=4 March 2019 |language=English |edition=2nd |year=2010 |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers |location=Leiden|isbn=978-90-04-18004-8}}</ref>\n\n== Role ==\nThe Group, as with all the regional groups, plays a major role in promoting the region's interests. It provides a forum for Member States to exchange opinions on international issues, carry out follow-up on the topics that are being discussed in international organisations, build common positions on complex issues and prepare statements reflecting the joint position of the Group.<ref name=\"Colombia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cancilleria.gov.co/en/content/latin-american-and-caribbean-group-grulac |title=Latin American and Caribbean Group (GRULAC) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Colombia |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Colombia |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rlc.fao.org/en/initiative/management-and-follow-up/grulac/ |title=Group of Latin American and Caribbean Countries in the United Nations (GRULAC) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations  |publisher=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025133120/http://www.rlc.fao.org/en/initiative/management-and-follow-up/grulac/ |archive-date=25 October 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHowever, most importantly, the Group allows for the discussion and coordination of support for candidates for different United Nations organisations from the region.<ref name =\"UNU Report\" />\n\n== Member States ==\nThe following are the Member States of the African Group:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.un.org/depts/DGACM/RegionalGroups.shtml |title=United Nations Regional Groups of Member States |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=United Nations Department for General Assembly and Conference management |publisher=United Nations |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=United Nations Handbook 2018\u201319 |url=https://www.mfat.govt.nz/assets/Handbooks/UN-Handbook-2018-19-pdf.pdf |edition=56 |location=Wellington |publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade of New Zealand |pages=15\u201317 |date=2018 |issn=0110-1951}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagcountry|Algeria}}\n*{{flagcountry|Angola}}\n*{{flagcountry|Benin}}\n*{{flagcountry|Botswana}}\n*{{flagcountry|Burkina Faso}}\n*{{flagcountry|Burundi}}\n*{{flagcountry|Cabo Verde}}\n*{{flagcountry|Cameroon}}\n*{{flagcountry|Central African Republic}}\n*{{flagcountry|Chad}}\n*{{flagcountry|Comoros}}\n*{{flagcountry|Congo}}\n*{{flagcountry|C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|name=C\u00f4te D'Ivoire}}\n*{{flagcountry|DRC}}\n*{{flagcountry|Djibouti}}\n*{{flagcountry|Egypt}}\n*{{flagcountry|Equatorial Guinea}}\n*{{flagcountry|Eritrea}}\n*{{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n*{{flagcountry|Swaziland|name=Eswatini}}\n*{{flagcountry|Gabon}}\n*{{flagcountry|Gambia|name=Gambia (Republic of The)}}\n*{{flagcountry|Ghana}}\n*{{flagcountry|Guinea}}\n*{{flagcountry|Guinea-Bissau}}\n*{{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n*{{flagcountry|Lesotho}}\n*{{flagcountry|Liberia}}\n*{{flagcountry|Libya}}\n*{{flagcountry|Madagascar}}\n*{{flagcountry|Malawi}}\n*{{flagcountry|Mali}}\n*{{flagcountry|Mauritania}}\n*{{flagcountry|Mauritius}}\n*{{flagcountry|Morocco}}\n*{{flagcountry|Mozambique}}\n*{{flagcountry|Namibia}}\n*{{flagcountry|Niger}}\n*{{flagcountry|Nigeria}}\n*{{flagcountry|Rwanda}}\n*{{flagcountry|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe}}\n*{{flagcountry|Senegal}}\n*{{flagcountry|Seychelles}}\n*{{flagcountry|Sierra Leone}}\n*{{flagcountry|Somalia}}\n*{{flagcountry|South Africa}}\n*{{flagcountry|South Sudan}}\n*{{flagcountry|Sudan}}\n*{{flagcountry|Togo}}\n*{{flagcountry|Tunisia}}\n*{{flagcountry|Uganda}}\n*{{flagcountry|Tanzania|name=United Republic of Tanzania}}\n*{{flagcountry|Zambia}}\n*{{flagcountry|Zimbabwe}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Representation ==\n=== Security Council ===\nThe African Group currently holds three seats on the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]], all non-permanent. The current members of the Security Council from the Group are:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/securitycouncil/content/current-members |title=Current Members |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=United Nations Security Council |publisher=United Nations |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2019/ga12152.doc.htm |title=General Assembly Elects Estonia, Niger, Saint Vincent and Grenadines, Tunisia, Viet Nam as Non-Permanent Members of Security Council for 2020-2021 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=7 June 2019 |website=United Nations Meetings Coverage & Press Releases |publisher=United Nations |access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Term\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|South Africa}}\n| 1 January 2019 \u2014 31 December 2020\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Niger}}\n| 1 January 2020 \u2014 31 December 2021\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Tunisia}}\n| 1 January 2020 \u2014 31 December 2021\n|}\n\n=== Economic and Social Council ===\nThe African Group currently holds 14 seats on the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]]. The current members of the Economic and Social Council from the Group are:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/ecosoc/en/content/members |title=Members |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=United Nations Economic and Social Council |publisher=United Nations |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2019/ga12153.doc.htm |title=General Assembly Elects 19 Economic and Social Council Members to Terms Beginning 1 January 2020, Adopts Resolution Commemorating Signing of United Nations Charter |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=14 June 2019 |website=United Nations Meetings Coverage & Press Releases |publisher=United Nations |access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Term\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Ghana}} \n| rowspan=5 | 1 January 2018 \u2013 31 December 2020 \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Malawi}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Morocco}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Sudan}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Togo}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Angola}} \n| rowspan=5 | 1 January 2019 \u2014  31 December 2021\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Egypt}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Kenya}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Mali}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Benin}} \n| rowspan=4 | 1 January 2020 \u2014 31 December 2022\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Botswana}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Congo}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Gabon}} \n|}\n\n=== Human Rights Council ===\nThe African Group currently holds 13 seats on the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]. The current members of the Economic and Social Council from the Group are:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/Pages/MembersByGroup.aspx |title=Current Membership of the Human Rights Council, 1 January - 31 December 2019 by regional groups |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=United Nations Human Rights Council |publisher=United Nations |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2019/ga12204.doc.htm |title=General Assembly Elects 14 Member States to Human Rights Council, Appoints New Under-Secretary-General for Internal Oversight Services |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=17 October 2019 |website=United Nations Meetings Coverage & Press Releases |publisher=United Nations |access-date=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Term\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Angola}} \n| rowspan=4 | 1 January 2018 \u2014 31 December 2020\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|DRC|name=Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Nigeria}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Senegal}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Burkina Faso}} \n| rowspan=5 | 1 January 2019 \u2014 31 December 2021\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Cameroon}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Eritrea}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Somalia}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Togo}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Libya}} \n| rowspan=4 | 1 January 2020 \u2014 31 December 2022\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Mauritania}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Namibia}} \n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Sudan}} \n|}\n\n=== Presidency of the General Assembly ===\nEvery five years in the years ending in 4 and 9, the African Group is eligible to elect a president to the General Assembly.<ref name= \"Worldatlas\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/what-are-the-five-regional-groups-of-the-united-nations.html |title=What Are The Five Regional Groups of the United Nations? |author=Wanza, Serah N. |date=27 November 2017 |website=Worldatlas |publisher=Worldatlas |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of presidents from the Gr\noup since its official creation in 1963:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/pga/73/about/past-presidents/ |title=Past Presidents |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=United Nations General Assembly |publisher=United Nations |access-date=27 February 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year Elected !! Session !! Name of President !! Country !! Note\n|-\n| 1964 || 19th || [[Alex Quaison-Sackey]] || {{Flagcountry|Ghana}} ||\n|-\n| 1969 || 24th || [[Angie Brooks|Angie E. Brooks]] || {{flagcountry|Liberia}} ||\n|-\n| 1974 || 29th || [[Abdelaziz Bouteflika]] || {{flagcountry|Algeria}} ||\n|-\n| 1979 || 34th || [[Salim Ahmed Salim|Salim A. Salim]] || {{flagcountry|Tanzania|name=United Republic of Tanzania}} || Also chaired the [[Sixth emergency special session of the United Nations General Assembly|6th]] and [[Seventh emergency special session of the United Nations General Assembly|7th]] emergency special, and 11th special sessions of the General Assembly\n|-\n| 1984 || 39th || [[Paul J. F. Lusaka]] || {{flagcountry|Zambia}} || \n|-\n| 1989 || 44th || [[Joseph Nanven Garba]] || {{flagcountry|Nigeria}} ||  Also chaired 16th, 17th and 18th special sessions of the General Assembly\n|-\n| 1994 || 49th || [[Amara Essy]] || {{flagcountry|C\u00f4te d'Ivoire|name=C\u00f4te d'Ivoire}} || \n|-\n| 1999 || 54th || [[Theo-Ben Gurirab]] || {{flagcountry| Namibia}}  || Also chaired the 22nd, 23rd and 24th special sessions of 