|| 54 || 22 || 17 || 15 || 40.74\n|| 50 || 20 || 17 || 13 || 40.00 || 1.54\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===League===\n*'''[[List of English football champions|Football League First Division]]''' (first tier)<ref name=\"divisions\">Up until 1992, the top division of [[Football in England|English football]] was the [[Football League First Division]]; since then, it has been the [[Premier League]]. Similarly until 1992, the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] was the second tier of league football, when it became the First Division, and is now known as [[Football League Championship|The Championship]]. The third tier was the Third Division until 1992, and is now known as [[League One]].</ref>\n** Champions: [[1888\u201389 Football League|1888\u201389]], [[1889\u201390 Football League|1889\u201390]]\n** Runners-up: [[1890\u201391 Football League|1890\u201391]], [[1891\u201392 Football League|1891\u201392]], [[1892\u201393 Football League|1892\u201393]], [[1905\u201306 Football League|1905\u201306]], [[1952\u201353 Football League|1952\u201353]], [[1957\u201358 Football League|1957\u201358]]\n*'''[[List of winners of English Football League Championship and predecessors|Football League Second Division/Football League First Division/Championship]]''' (second tier)<ref name=\"divisions\"/>\n** Champions: [[1903\u201304 Football League|1903\u201304]], [[1912\u201313 Football League|1912\u201313]], [[1950\u201351 Football League|1950\u201351]]\n** Runners-up: [[1914\u201315 Football League|1914\u201315]], [[1933\u201334 Football League|1933\u201334]]\n** Play-off Runners-up: [[2001 Football League First Division play-off Final|2000\u201301]], [[2005 Football League Championship play-off Final|2004\u201305]]\n** Play-off Semi-finalists: [[2005\u201306 Football League#Championship play-offs|2005\u201306]], [[2008\u201309 Football League#Play-offs|2008\u201309]]\n*'''[[List of winners of English Football League One and predecessors|Football League Third Division/Football League Second Division/League 1]]''' (third tier)<ref name=\"divisions\"/>\n** Champions: [[1970\u201371 Football League|1970\u201371]], [[1999\u20132000 Football League|1999\u20132000]]\n** Play-off Winners: [[2014\u201315 Football League#League One play-offs|2014\u201315]]\n** Play-off Semi-finalists: [[1988\u201389 Football League#Third Division play-offs|1988\u201389]], [[1998\u201399 Football League#Second Division play-offs|1998\u201399]], [[2013\u201314 Football League#Play-offs 2|2013\u201314]]\n*'''[[List of winners of English Football League Two and predecessors|Football League Fourth Division/Football League Third Division/League 2]]''' (fourth tier)<ref name=\"divisions\"/>\n** Champions: [[1995\u201396 Football League|1995\u201396]]\n** Runners-up: [[1986\u201387 Football League|1986\u201387]]\n** Play-off Runners-up: [[1993\u201394 Football League#Third Division play-offs|1993\u201394]]\n** Play-off Semi-finalists: [[1994\u201395 Football League#Third Division play-offs|1994\u201395]]\n\n===Cup===\n*'''[[FA Cup]]'''\n** Winners: [[1889 FA Cup Final|1888\u201389]], [[1938 FA Cup Final|1937\u201338]]\n** Runners-up: [[1922 FA Cup Final|1921\u201322]], [[1954 FA Cup Final|1953\u201354]], [[1964 FA Cup Final|1963\u201364]]\n\n*'''[[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]]'''\n** Runners-up: [[1938 FA Charity Shield|1938]]\n\n*'''[[Football League War Cup]]'''\n** Winners: [[1940\u201341 in English football|1940\u201341]]\n\n* '''[[Lancashire Senior Cup]]'''\n**Winners: 1886\u201387, 1892\u201393, 1894\u201395, 1899\u20131900, 1938\u201339, 1996\u201397\n\n===Other===\nIn 1996, Preston's Third Division title made them the third club to have been champions of all four professional leagues in English football. This feat has also been achieved by [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in 1988, local rivals [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in 1992, and both [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in 2017.\n\n==Club records==\n\n*Most Goals (Overall): [[Tom Finney]], 210 goals from 473 appearances.\n*Most League Goals: Tom Finney, 187 goals from 433 appearances.\n*Most League Goals in a Season: [[Ted Harper]], '''37''' in [[Football League Second Division]], [[1932-33 in English football|1932\u201333]]<ref name=Milestones/>\n*Record Attendance: '''42,684''' v [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Football League First Division]], 23 April 1938<ref name=Milestones>{{cite web|title=Milestones |url=http://www.pnefc.net/page/History/0,,10362~1033950,00.html |publisher=Preston North End FC |accessdate=22 November 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307022304/http://www.pnefc.net/page/History/0%2C%2C10362~1033950%2C00.html |archivedate= 7 March 2009 |date=3 January 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*Record Cup Victory: '''26\u20130''' v [[Hyde F.C.|Hyde]], FA Cup, 15 October 1887<ref name=Milestones/>\n*Record League Victory: '''10\u20130''' v [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]], [[Football League Division One]], 14 September 1889<ref name=Milestones/>\n*Record Defeat: '''0\u20137''' v [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], Division 1, 1 May 1948\n*Transfer Record (Paid): ''' \u00a32,000,000''' for [[Tom Bayliss]] from [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], January 2019<ref name=PottsSale>{{cite web|title=Brad Potts:Midfielder Brad Potts Joins Preston in a Club Record Deal for North End|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley-midfielder-brad-potts-joins-preston-in-a-club-record-deal-for-north-end-1-9519658|work=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=4 January 2018|date=3 January 2018}}</ref>\n*Transfer Record (Received): '''\u00a39,000,000''' for [[Jordan Hugill]] to [[West Ham Utd]], January 2018<ref name=HugillSale>{{cite web|title=Jordan Hugill: West Ham sign Preston striker in reported \u00a310m deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42895867|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 January 2018|date=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n*Youngest Ever Player: [[Ethan Walker]] 16 years and 156 days\n*Oldest Ever Player: [[Bob Kelly (footballer)|Bob Kelly]] 41 years and two months<ref>{{cite news|title=Age is just a number&nbsp;\u2013 Graham Alexander|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15243376.stm|accessdate=27 November 2011|work=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Rivals==\n{{See also|Preston North End F.C. league record by opponent}}\nHistorically, Preston North End's main rivalry has been with [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] and the [[West Lancashire derby]] between the two clubs has been contested across all four divisions of the [[Football League]] since 1901.<ref>{{cite news | title=Rivalry uncovered! The results of the largest ever survey into club rivalries |publisher=The Football Fans Census |date=December 2003 | url=http://www.footballfanscensus.com/issueresults/Club_Rivalries_Uncovered_Results.pdf | format=[[PDF]] | accessdate=27 November 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304004344/http://www.footballfanscensus.com/issueresults/Club_Rivalries_Uncovered_Results.pdf | archivedate=4 March 2009 |df=dmy}}</ref> Preston's other local rivals in the league over the years have included [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and [[Wigan Athletic A.F.C.|Wigan Athletic]].\n\n==Sponsors==\nThe club's main sponsors since shirt sponsorship was introduced in 1979 have been as follows:<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Preston_North_End/Preston_North_End.html | title=Preston North End&nbsp;\u2013 Sponsors Through the Years | publisher=Historicalkits.co.uk | date=2018 | accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\"|Years\n! style=\"background:silver;\"|Sponsor(s)\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 1979\u20131984 || [[Pontins]]\n|-\n| 1984\u20131985 || David Leil\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 1985\u20131986 || Lombard Continental\n|-\n| 1986\u20131990 || Garratt's Insurance\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 1990\u20131992|| Ribble Valley Shelving\n|-\n| 1992\u20131995 || [[Coloroll]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 1995\u20132002 || [[Baxi]]\n|-\n| 2002\u20132005 || New Reg\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 2005\u20132010|| [[Enterprise plc|Enterprise]]\n|-\n| 2010\u20132012 || [[Tennent's]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 2012\u20132013 || [[Magners]]\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014 || [[Sportech|The Football Pools]]/[[The Princess Royal Trust for Carers|Carers Trust]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 2014\u20132016 || [[Virgin Trains]]\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017 || |[[888sport]]\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 2017\u20132018 || Tempobet\n|-\n|2018\u2013\n|[[32Red]]\n|}\n\n==Women's football==\n{{Main article|Preston North End W.F.C.}}\nThe previously affiliated [[Women's association football|women's football]] team was called [[Preston North End W.F.C.]] In May 2016, they became Fylde Ladies F.C., in association with [[National League North]] side [[A.F.C. Fylde]].<ref name=PNEWFC>{{cite web|title=PNE women's team have fresh start as Fylde Ladies|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/football/afc-fylde/pne-women-s-team-have-fresh-start-as-fylde-ladies-1-7929437|publisher=Blackpool Gazette|accessdate=2 June 2016|date=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.pnefc.net/ Official Website]\n* [http://www.lep.co.uk/sport/football/preston-north-end PNE section on [[Lancashire Evening Post]] online site]\n* [http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2054&teamTabs=results Preston North End at [[Racing Post#Soccerbase|Soccerbase]]]\n* [http://www.spartacus-educational.com/Fpreston.htm History of Preston North End: 1862\u20131945]\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/record.php?id=17597 Online video footage of Preston North End winning the 1938 FA Cup]\n* {{BBC Football Info|BBClinkname=preston-north-end}}\n* [http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/barnsley-midfielder-brad-potts-joins-preston-in-a-club-record-deal-for-north-end-1-9519658 Article relating to transfer of Brad Potts to Preston North End]\n\n{{Preston North End F.C.}}\n{{Preston North End F.C. seasons}}\n{{Original Football League clubs}}\n{{Football League Championship}}\n{{City of Preston culture}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Preston North End F.C.]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1880]]\n[[Category:FA Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:The Football League founder members]]\n[[Category:Sport in Preston]]\n[[Category:1880 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Preston, Lancashire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Association football club}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname      = Preston North End\n| image         = PNE FC.png\n| image_size    = 180px\n| fullname      = Preston North End Football Club\n| nickname      = The Lilywhites\n| founded       = {{Start date and age|1880}}\n| ground        = [[Deepdale]]\n| capacity      = 23,404\n| manager       = [[Alex Neil (footballer)|Alex Neil]]\n| league        = {{English football updater|PrestoNE}}\n| season        = {{English football updater|PrestoNE2}}\n| position      = {{English football updater|PrestoNE3}}\n| website       = http://www.pnefc.net/\n| current       = 2019\u201320 Preston North End F.C. season\n| pattern_la1   = \n| pattern_b1    = _preston1920h\n| pattern_ra1   = \n| pattern_sh1   =\n| pattern_so1   = _pnefc201920h\n| leftarm1      = FFFFFF\n| body1         = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1     = FFFFFF\n| shorts1       = 040040\n| socks1        = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2   = \n| pattern_b2    = _pne1920a\n| pattern_ra2   = \n| pattern_sh2   =\n| pattern_so2   =\n| leftarm2      = FFDD00\n| body2         = FFDD00\n| rightarm2     = FFDD00\n| shorts2       = FFDD00\n| socks2        = FFDD00\n| pattern_la3   = _preston1819a\n| pattern_b3    = _preston1819a\n| pattern_ra3   = _preston1819a\n| pattern_sh3   =\n| pattern_so3   =\n| leftarm3      = 008000\n| body3         = 138022\n| rightarm3     = 008000\n| shorts3       = FFDD00\n| socks3        = FFDD00\n}}\n'''Preston North End Football Club''' (often shortened to '''The North End or PNE''') is a professional [[association football|football]] club in [[Preston, Lancashire]], whose team currently plays in the [[EFL Championship]], the second tier of the [[English football league system]]. Originally a [[cricket]] club, Preston have been based at [[Deepdale]] since 1875. The club first took up football in 1878 as a winter fitness activity and decided to focus on it in May 1880, when the football club was officially founded. Deepdale is now football's oldest ground in terms of continuous use by a major league club.\n\nPreston North End was a founder member of the [[English Football League|Football League]] in 1888. In the [[1888\u201389 in English football|1888\u201389 season]], the team won both the [[List of English football champions|inaugural league championship]] and the [[1889 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]], the latter without conceding a goal. They were the first team to achieve the \"[[Double (association football)|Double]]\" in English football and, as they were unbeaten in all matches, are remembered as \"[[The Invincibles (football)|The Invincibles]]\". Preston won the league championship again in 1889\u201390 but their only major success since then has been their [[1938 FA Cup Final]] victory over [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. The club's most famous players have been [[Tom Finney]] and [[Bill Shankly]], who are both commemorated at Deepdale by stands named after them. Other notable players include [[Tommy Docherty]], [[Alan Kelly Sr.]] and [[Graham Alexander]].\n\nUntil 1961, Preston were usually members of the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] but, having been relegated after the [[1960\u201361 in English football|1960\u201361 season]], they have not yet returned to the top flight. They were first relegated to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] after the [[1969\u201370 in English football|1969\u201370 season]] and have spent 28 of the 49 seasons since 1970 in the bottom two divisions, including a span of 19 seasons from 1981-1982 to 1999\u20132000. Preston have faced serious financial issues and were twice in danger of closure. The club is now owned by businessman [[Trevor Hemmings]] and has been established in the EFL Championship since gaining promotion in 2015.\n\n==History==\n{{Main article|History of Preston North End F.C.}}\n[[File:Preston North End FC League Performance.svg|thumb|300px|Chart showing the progress of Preston North End F.C. through the [[English football league system]].]]\nPreston North End was founded in 1863, originally as a [[cricket]] club, and played their first matches at the Marsh near the [[River Ribble]] in the [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] suburb of [[Ashton-on-Ribble|Ashton]]. Later that year, they switched to [[Moor Park, Preston|Moor Park]] in the north of the town, calling themselves \"North End\" in recognition of the new location. On 21 January 1875, the club leased a field opposite Moor Park on the site of the current [[Deepdale]] stadium, which has been its home ever since.<ref name=hist>{{cite web | url=http://www.pnefc.net/club/history/ | title=Preston North End FC History | publisher=Preston North End | date=2018 | accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe club formed a [[rugby union]] team in 1877 as a winter fitness activity but this was not a success and, a year later, they played their first game under the [[Laws of the Game (association football)|rules of association football]]. In May 1880, a proposal to fully adopt the association code was unanimously accepted and Preston North End Football Club was officially founded.<ref name=\"hist\"/>\n\nPreston became one of the first professional clubs by hiring players from Scotland. In [[1887\u201388 FA Cup|1887]], they beat [[Hyde F.C.|Hyde]] 26\u20130 in the first round of the FA Cup, still a record winning margin in English first-class football. Scottish forward [[Jimmy Ross (footballer born 1866)|Jimmy Ross]] scored eight goals in the match before going on to score 19 goals in the competition that season, also still a record.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thefa.com/Competitions/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/facupheroes | title=FA Cup Heroes | publisher=[[The Football Association]] | accessdate=10 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThey played [[Hibernian F.C.]] in [[1887 World Championship (football)|1887 World Championship]] losing 2\u20131 in [[Edinburgh]].\n\n[[File:Preston north end art.jpg|thumb|250px|Preston North End in 1888\u201389, the first Football League champions, subsequently doing '[[Double (association football)|The Double]]']]\nIn [[1888-89 in English football|1888\u201389]], Preston became the first league champions and the first winners of \"[[Double (association football)|The Double]]\", becoming the only team to date to go throughout an entire season unbeaten in both the league and [[FA Cup]]&nbsp;\u2013 winning the FA Cup without conceding a goal.<ref name=\"Arsenal\">In [[2003-04 in English football|2003\u201304]], [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] also achieved [[2003\u201304 Arsenal F.C. season|an unbeaten season in the top flight]], but they went out of the FA Cup at the semi-final stage.</ref> In a contribution to Paul Agnew's 1989 biography of [[Tom Finney]], the player himself wrote: \"The club has long been known as Proud Preston, and the Old Invincibles of the previous century set some incredible standards\".<ref>Agnew, p. 55.</ref> The author wrote elsewhere: \"...and that team became immortalised as the 'Old Invincibles'\".<ref>Agnew, p. 53.</ref> Other sources call the team \"The Invincibles\" and both versions of the nickname have been used.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/6025037.Remembering_when_Preston_were_The_Invincibles/ | title=Remembering when Preston were The Invincibles | work=Bolton News | date=15 June 2001 | accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> In his autobiography, Finney wrote: \"The championship stayed with North End \u2014 by now tagged the Old Invincibles \u2014 the following year, but runners-up spot had to suffice for the next three seasons\".<ref>{{cite book | last=Finney | first=Tom | authorlink=Tom Finney | title=Tom Finney \u2013 My Autobiography | page=113 | year=2003 | publisher=Headline Publishing | location=London | isbn=0-7553-1106-X}}</ref> As Finney said, Preston were league champions again in 1889\u201390, but have not won the title since. In total, they have been league runners-up six times, including the three consecutive seasons from 1890 to 1891 to 1892\u201393, and twice in the 1950s when Finney was playing. The club's last major trophy win was in the [[1938 FA Cup Final]] when they defeated [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] 1\u20130 and the team included [[Bill Shankly]], [[Andy Beattie]] and goalscorer [[George Mutch]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.soccerbase.com/matches/results.sd?date=1938-04-30 | title=Results & Matches on Saturday, 30 Apr 1938 | work=Racing Post | date=2018 | accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nPreston's most famous player, [[Tom Finney]], joined the club as a teenager in 1938. His first team debut was delayed until 1946 by the [[World War II|Second World War]] but he played for Preston until he retired in 1960. He was nicknamed the \"Preston Plumber\" because of his local business. Finney remains the club's top goalscorer, with 187 goals from 433 appearances, and also scored 30 international goals for [[England national football team|England]] in 76 appearances.<ref>Finney, ''My Autobiography'', pp. 415\u2013419.</ref>\n\nA year after Finney's retirement, Preston were relegated to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] and have not played in the top division since. They had a memorable [[1963\u201364 in English football|season in 1963\u201364]] when, managed by former player [[Jimmy Milne (footballer, born 1911)|Jimmy Milne]], they finished third in the Second Division and reached the [[1964 FA Cup Final]] where they lost a thrilling match 3\u20132 to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. \n\nPreston were first relegated to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] after the [[1969\u201370 in English football|1969\u201370 season]]. Although they won promotion again immediately, the team have spent 28 of the 49 seasons since 1970 in the bottom two divisions, including a span of 19 seasons from 1981 to 1982 to 1999\u20132000. The club experienced a near-terminal decline in the 1980s which brought about the very real threat of closure, the nadir being the [[1985\u201386 Football League|1985\u201386 season]] when they finished 23rd in the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] and had to seek re-election to the league. \n\n[[File:David Moyes (201551591).jpg|thumb|right|180px|Under [[David Moyes]], Preston were [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] champions in 2000, and narrowly missed out on promotion to the Premier League the following season.]]\nUnder manager [[John McGrath (footballer born 1938)|John McGrath]], the team recovered and won promotion back to the Third Division only a year later but it was a false dawn as the team spent another three years in the bottom division from 1993 to 1996. The club finally began to recover and move forward after a takeover by heating manufacturer [[Baxi]] in 1994 but their ownership ended in June 2002.<ref name=\"Col\">{{cite news | url=https://www.lep.co.uk/sport/football/preston-north-end/col-backed-baxi-s-pne-revolution-1-6425720 | title=Col backed Baxi's PNE revolution | work=Lancashire Evening Post | date=8 February 2014 | accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Baxi\">{{cite web | url=https://www.lep.co.uk/news/baxi-in-pne-sell-off-1-101554 | title=Baxi in PNE sell-off | work=Lancashire Evening Post | date=28 June 2002 | accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> The team's central defender [[David Moyes]], then aged 34, began his managerial career when appointed by the Baxi-controlled board in February 1998. Moyes was successful and managed the team to the [[1999\u20132000 Football League#Second Division|third tier championship]] in 2000. Preston reached the [[2000\u201301 Football League#First Division play-offs|2001 play-off final]] but were defeated by [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]. In the [[2005 Football League play-offs|2005 play-off final]], under Moyes' successor [[Billy Davies]], Preston were beaten 1\u20130 by West Ham United.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/4573799.stm | title=West Ham 1\u20130 Preston | publisher=BBC Sport | date=30 May 2005 | accessdate=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Baxi sell-off and the departure of Moyes to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in 2002, the team was established at second tier level through the 2000s but more problems arose at the end of the decade with an [[HM Revenue and Customs]] winding-up order in 2010 and relegation to the third tier in 2011. The taxation issue was resolved by local businessman [[Trevor Hemmings]], already a shareholder, who bought a controlling interest in June 2010.<ref name=\"Hemmings\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/preston/8722002.stm | title=Deal agreed for Preston North End takeover | publisher=BBC Sport | date=4 June 2010 | accessdate=6 August 2018}}</ref> The team were promoted again, via the play-offs, in 2015 and have been well-placed in the [[EFL Championship]] since then. \n\nDeepdale was the original cricket club's home from 1875 and has been a football venue from 1878. It is the world's oldest football ground in terms of continuous use by a club in a major league. When Baxi took control, it embarked on an investment programme which had the main goal of upgrading Deepdale into a modern stadium. The old ground was demolished and rebuilt in four stages and the last of the new stands was opened in 2008. Part of the redevelopment was the original [[National Football Museum]] which opened at Deepdale in 2001, but it was relocated to Manchester in 2012 after being closed for two years. Preston have had the fair share of results at Deepdale, they beat Blackpool 1\u20130 in the 86' and pitch invaded.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-18725667 | title=National Football Museum opens at new Manchester home | last=Airey | first=Tom | date=6 July 2012 | work=BBC News | accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Ground==\n{{Main article|Deepdale}}\n[[File:Deepdalecomplete.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Deepdale stadium.]]\nThe site of the current [[Deepdale|Deepdale stadium]] was first leased by the club in 1875 and was first used for association football in 1878. The biggest attendance seen was 42,684 for a Division One clash with Arsenal in April 1938. Following a complete reconstruction between 1996 and 2009, the stadium has a seated capacity of 23,404. The current pitch dimensions are 110 x 75 yards.<ref name=\"FGG\">{{cite web | url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/leagues/england/championship/deepdale-preston-north-end.html | title=Deepdale \u2013 Preston North End | publisher=Football Ground Guide (FGG) | date=2018 | accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Statue===\n[[File:Finney.jpg|thumb|right|190px|''The Splash'' commemorates Preston legend [[Tom Finney]].]]\nOutside the Sir Tom Finney Stand is a statue of the famous player himself, which is known as \"The Splash\" or the \"Tom Finney Splash\". The statue, sculpted by [[Peter Hodgkinson]] and unveiled in July 2004, was inspired by a famous photograph taken at the [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] versus PNE game in 1956, played at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in particularly wet conditions.<ref name=\"FGG\"/>\n\n==Players==\n{{updated|31 January 2020}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.pnefc.net/teams/first-team/ | title=Preston North End \u2013 First Team Squad | publisher=Preston North End F.C. | date=2018 | accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Current squad===\n{{fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1 |nat=ENG | pos=GK |name=[[Declan Rudd]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=2 |nat=ENG | pos=DF |name=[[Darnell Fisher]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=4 |nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=[[Ben Pearson (footballer)|Ben Pearson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5 |nat=ENG | pos=DF |name=[[Tom Clarke (footballer, born 1987)|Tom Clarke]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6 |nat=ENG | pos=DF |name=[[Ben Davies (footballer, born 1995)|Ben Davies]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=7 |nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=[[Tom Bayliss]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8 |nat=IRE | pos=MF |name=[[Alan Browne (footballer)|Alan Browne]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9 |nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[Louis Moult]]}} \n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=[[Josh Harrop]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=JAM | pos=MF |name=[[Daniel Johnson (footballer)|Daniel Johnson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=SCO | pos=MF |name=[[Paul Gallagher (footballer)|Paul Gallagher]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=WAL | pos=GK |name=[[Michael Crowe (footballer)|Michael Crowe]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=ENG | pos=DF |name=[[Jordan Storey]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=IRL | pos=DF |name=[[Joe Rafferty]]}}\n{{fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=WAL | pos=DF |name=[[Andrew Hughes (footballer, born 1992)|Andrew Hughes]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=[[Ryan Ledson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=20|nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[Jayden Stockley]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=GER | pos=DF |name=[[Patrick Bauer (footballer)|Patrick Bauer]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=23|nat=ENG | pos=DF |name=[[Paul Huntington]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=24|nat=IRL | pos=FW |name=[[Sean Maguire (footballer)|Sean Maguire]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=ENG | pos=GK |name=[[Connor Ripley]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=28|nat=ENG | pos=GK |name=[[Mathew Hudson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=29|nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[Tom Barkhuizen]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=31|nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[Scott Sinclair]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=35|nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[David Nugent]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=39|nat=WAL | pos=FW |name=[[Billy Bodin]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=41|nat=SCO | pos=DF |name=Lewis Coulton}}\n{{Fs player|no=44|nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=[[Brad Potts]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===On loan===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=3 |nat=ENG | pos=DF |name=[[Josh Earl (footballer)|Josh Earl]]|other=on loan at [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=[[Josh Ginnelly]]|other=on loan at [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=27|nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[Connor Simpson]]|other=on loan at [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=30|nat=ENG | pos=MF |name=Jack Baxter|other=on loan at [[Clitheroe F.C.|Clitheroe]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=32|nat=IRL | pos=MF |name=[[Adam O'Reilly]]|other=on loan at [[Stalybridge Celtic F.C.|Stalybridge Celtic]] until the end of the 2019\u201320 season}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=33|nat=ENG | pos=FW |name=[[Ethan Walker]]|other=on loan at [[Stalybridge Celtic F.C.|Stalybridge Celtic]] until the end of the 2019\u201320 season}}\n{{Fs player|no=34|nat=SCO | pos=DF |name=Jack Armer|other=on loan at [[Lancaster City F.C.|Lancaster City]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=IRL | pos=FW |name=[[Graham Burke]]|other=on loan at [[Shamrock Rovers F.C.|Shamrock Rovers]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=IRL | pos=DF |name=[[Kevin O'Connor (footballer, born 1995)|Kevin O'Connor]]|other=on loan at [[Waterford F.C.|Waterford]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Former players===\n{{Main article|List of Preston North End F.C. players}}\n<!-- Do not list former players here; any notable players should instead be detailed in the main \"List of Preston North End F.C. players\" article -->\n\n==Technical staff==\nBelow is a list of non-playing personnel:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pnefc.net/teams/management/|title=First Team Management|publisher=PNEFC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pnefc.net/teams/academy-staff/|title=Academy Staff|publisher=PNEFC}}</ref>\n{| class=\"toccolours\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:silver;\"|Name\n! style=\"background:silver;\"|Role\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| [[Alex Neil (footballer)|Alex Neil]] || Manager\n|-\n| Frankie McAvoy || Assistant Manager\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| [[Steve Thompson (footballer, born 1964)|Steve Thompson]]  || First Team Coach\n|-\n| [[Jonathan Gould]] || Goalkeeping Coach\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| Matt Jackson || First Team Physio\n|- \n| Tom Little  || Fitness Coach\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n|  Nick Harrison || Academy Manager\n|-\n| Joe Savage  || Head of Recruitment\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n|Daniel Steve Cowell||Kitman\n|}\n\n==Managerial history==\n{{Main article|List of Preston North End F.C. managers}}\n{{updated|23 August 2018}}\nThe following is a list of Preston North End managers since 1986, excluding caretakers:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnefc.net/page/History/0,,10362~1033968,00.html |title=List of Preston North End F.C. Managers |publisher=Preston North End |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120722131111/http://www.pnefc.net/page/History/0%2C%2C10362~1033968%2C00.html |archivedate=22 July 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?team_id=2054&teamTabs=managers|title=Preston Manager History \u2013 Past & Present \u2013 Soccer Base|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Manager\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nationality\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Period\n!colspan=\"5\"|Total\n!colspan=\"6\"|League\n|-\n!G !! W!! D!! L!! Win %!!G !! W!! D!! L!! Win %!! Point Av.\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[John McGrath (footballer born 1938)|John McGrath]] ||align=\"left\"| {{ENG}}  || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1986\u20131990\n|| 192 || 74 ||53|| 65|| 38.54\n|