ussels-1987|title=Brussels 1987|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-bgcolor=#F88379\n| {{YUG}} {{dagger}}\n| [[Zagreb]]<br><small>(present day Croatia)</small>\n| [[Vatroslav Lisinski Concert Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 1990|1990]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/zagreb-1990|title=Zagreb 1990|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{EST}}\n| [[Tallinn]]\n| [[Saku Suurhall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2002|2002]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/tallinn-2002|title=Tallinn 2002|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{LAT}}\n| [[Riga]]\n| [[Skonto Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2003|2003]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/riga-2003|title=Riga 2003|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{TUR}}\n| [[Istanbul]]\n| [[Abdi \u0130pek\u00e7i Arena]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/istanbul-2004|title=Istanbul 2004|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{GRE}}\n| [[Athens]]\n| [[Olympic Indoor Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006|2006]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/athens-2006|title=Athens 2006|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{FIN}}\n| [[Helsinki]]\n| [[Hartwall Areena|Hartwall Arena]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/helsinki-2007|title=Helsinki 2007|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{SRB}}\n| [[Belgrade]]\n| [[Beogradska Arena|Belgrade Arena]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/belgrade-2008|title=Belgrade 2008|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{RUS}}\n| [[Moscow]]\n| [[Olympic Stadium (Moscow arena)|Olympic Stadium]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/moscow-2009|title=Moscow 2009|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{AZE}}\n| [[Baku]]\n| [[Baku Crystal Hall]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/baku-2012|title=Baku 2012|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{POR}}\n| [[Lisbon]]\n| [[Altice Arena]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/event/lisbon-2018|title=Lisbon 2018|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Celebratory events==\n===Anniversary events===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Anniversary\n!Country\n!City\n!Venue\n!Event\n!Year\n|-\n| 25th\n| {{NOR}}\n| [[Mysen]]\n| [[Momarken]]\n| [[Songs of Europe (1981 concert)|Songs of Europe]]\n| 1981\n|-\n| 50th\n| {{DEN}}\n| [[Copenhagen]]\n| [[Forum Copenhagen]]\n| [[Congratulations: 50 Years of the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n| 2005\n|-\n| 60th\n| {{GBR}}\n| [[London]]\n| [[Eventim Apollo]]\n| [[Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits]]\n| 2015\n|-\n|}\n===Replacement events===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Country\n!Event\n!Replacing\n!Reason\n|-\n|2020\n|[[File:Flag_of_the_Netherlands.svg|link=Netherlands|alt=Netherlands|23x23px]] [[Netherlands|The Netherlands]]\n|''[[Eurovision: Europe Shine a Light|Eurovision: Europe Shine A Light]]''\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]]\n|[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak]]\n|}\n\n==Host City Insignia==\n[[File:ESC Host City Insignia.jpg|thumb|175px|right|The Host City Insignia on display inside the [[Rathaus,_Vienna|Rathaus]] in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], in May 2015. ]]\n'''Host City Insignia''' is a rotating trophy awarded to cities hosting the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. The symbol is a large key ring to which the Eurovision Song Contest Host Cities can attach their city key or other symbol representing the city. The Host City Insignia Exchange usually takes place in conjunction with the Semi-Final Allocation Draw. The insignia is traditionally put on display in a public place, such as the City Hall or another venue of local significance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/about/in-depth/host-city-insignia-exchange/|title=Host City Insignia Exchange|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> Additionally, there is a fob with a picture of the [[Helsinki Senate Square]] attached to the key ring.\n\nThe idea of the rotating trophy was proposed jointly by the City of [[Helsinki]], the Finnish Broadcasting Company [[YLE]] and [[EBU]] in connection with the 2007 Eurovision Song Contest. Hand-engraved on the ring are the following texts: \"Eurovision Song Contest Host City\", all Host Cities up until the year 2006 and a stamp: Helsinki 2007 with the initials of the prize designers. The concept and fob were designed by the ANTEEKSI Team and the ring by jewellery designer Taru Tonder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Badzic|first1=Milenko|title=Host City Insignia Exchange & Semi-Final Allocation Draw|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/press/photo-downloads?gal=123813&type=Press|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=26 March 2017|date=26 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327081350/http://www.eurovision.tv/page/press/photo-downloads?gal=123813&type=Press|archivedate=27 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212182218/http://www.hel.fi/wps/portal/Hallintokeskus_en/Artikkeli?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=%2FHalke%2Fen%2FNews%20and%20Press%20releases%2FUutiset|title=Open Doors Weekend fills Helsinki with design|website=City of Helsinki news|date=31 January 2012|language=Finnish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611105333/http://www.hel.fi/wps/portal/Hallintokeskus/Artikkeli?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=%2FHalke%2Ffi%2Fuutiset%2Bja%2Btiedotteet%2Fhallintokeskuksen%2Btiedotteet%2Fhelsinki%2Baloittaa%2Buuden%2Beurovision%2Blaulukilpailun%2Bperinteen|trans-title=Helsinki begins the tradition of the new Eurovision Song Contest|title=Helsinki aloittaa uuden Eurovision laulukilpailun perinteen|language=Finnish|date=15 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Semi-final allotment drawing venue==\nSince the introduction in [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]] of the two semi-finals system, a drawing has been held to determine in which semi-final a country would participate, as well as in which semi-final a country would vote in. Each year, either five or six countries are exempt from the drawing for competing in the semi-finals: the big-five (France, Germany, Italy, Spain, and UK), and the host country, if the host is not one of the big five. In [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015|2015]] the number of countries exempt was seven, as Australia joined the other six countries exempt because the country was considered a special guest contestant.\n\nRegardless if a country is exempt from competing in the semi-finals, all participating countries are allotted a semi-final in which to vote. \n \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Venue\n! City\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n| [[Stari dvor|Old Palace]]\n| [[Belgrade]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n| Marriott Royal Aurora Hotel\n| [[Moscow]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n| ''Euroclub'' at {{ill|Smuget|no}}\n| [[Oslo]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n| Esprit Arena\n| [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012}}\n| [[Buta Palace]]\n| [[Baku]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013}}\n| {{ill|Malm\u00f6 City Hall|sv|Malm\u00f6 r\u00e5dhus}}\n| [[Malm\u00f6]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014}}\n| [[Copenhagen City Hall]]\n| [[Copenhagen]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2015}}\n| [[Vienna City Hall|Vienna Rathaus]]\n| [[Vienna]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2016}}\n| [[Stockholm City Hall]]\n| [[Stockholm]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2017}}\n| Column Hall of [[Kiev City State Administration]]\n| [[Kiev]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018}}\n| [[Lisbon City Hall]]\n| [[Lisbon]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019}}\n| [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]]\n| [[Tel Aviv]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2020}}\n| Rotterdam City Hall \n| [[Rotterdam]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Running order drawing venue==\nFor the 1988 and 1997 contests, both held in Dublin, the running order was announced at a dedicated event.\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Venue\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1988}}\n| [[Mansion House, Dublin]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stillslibrary.rte.ie/indexplus/result.html?_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXACTION_=query&_IXFIRST_=6&_IXSR_=Rq6LMH0FNOO&_IXSS_=_IXMAXHITS_=10&_IXFPFX_=templates%252ft&_IXFIRST_=1&%252asform=%252fweb%252fsearch_forms%252fadvanced&%2524%253dsi=text&_IXACTION_=query&_IXINITSR_=y&%2524%253dsort=sort+descending+sortexpr+image_sort&search=search&%252aiexe+SECURITY_filter=%252e&%2524%253ds=eurovision+song+contest+draw&text_search_context=Eurovision+Song+Contest+draw&%253cphoto_taken_date_earliest=&_IXSPFX_=templates/t&_IXFPFX_=templates/t|title=RT\u00c9 Archives|first=RT\u00c9|last=Archives|date=5 July 2012|website=stillslibrary.rte.ie}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|1997}}\n| [[Clarence Hotel]], Dublin\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stillslibrary.rte.ie/indexplus/result.html?_IXMAXHITS_=1&_IXACTION_=query&_IXFIRST_=1&_IXSR_=Rq6LMH0FNOO&_IXSS_=_IXMAXHITS_=10&_IXFPFX_=templates%252ft&_IXFIRST_=1&%252asform=%252fweb%252fsearch_forms%252fadvanced&%2524%253dsi=text&_IXACTION_=query&_IXINITSR_=y&%2524%253dsort=sort+descending+sortexpr+image_sort&search=search&%252aiexe+SECURITY_filter=%252e&%2524%253ds=eurovision+song+contest+draw&text_search_context=Eurovision+Song+Contest+draw&%253cphoto_taken_date_earliest=&_IXSPFX_=templates/t&_IXFPFX_=templates/t|title=RT\u00c9 Archives|first=RT\u00c9|last=Archives|date=5 July 2012|website=stillslibrary.rte.ie}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Opening ceremony venue==\nOn opening ceremony organised by the host country has taken place since 2007. The event seeks to welcome the participating countries and mark the official start of the contest.\n;Table key\n{{legend|#A4EAA9|Contest cancelled|text=X}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Venue\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007}}\n| [[Finlandia Hall]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/music-eurovision-dc-idUSN0330320720070304|title=Finland prepares for its Eurovision close-up|date=4 March 2007|accessdate=20 April 2020|publisher=[[Reuters]]|first=Olaf|last=Furniss}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008}}\n| [[Palace of Serbia]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/palata-srbije-gets-ready-for-opening-party|title=Palata Srbije gets ready for opening party|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=18 May 2008|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009}}\n| [[Moscow Manege|Central Manezh Exhibition Center]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2009/05/11/eurovision-2009s-grand-opening-a1342|title=Eurovision 2009's Grand Opening|date=11 May 2009|website=The Moscow Times|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010}}\n| [[Oslo City Hall]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/oslo-welcomes-the-stars|title=Oslo welcomes the stars!|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=23 May 2010|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2011}}\n| [[Tonhalle D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/tonight-opening-reception-takes-place-in-duesseldorf|title=Tonight: Opening Reception takes place in D\u00fcsseldorf|date=May 7, 2011|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]}}</ref>\n|-\